Inspiration from EDA to deal with missing values:¶

Missing values for Class 0:¶

EDA 1. correlation matrix shows that features are uncorrelated EDA 2. Box plot and Density curve shows that each feature contains outlier. Moreover, missing values were replaced by 0, so ignore the occurance of 0 than the distribution of features is guassian.

Steps for filling missing values for each feature:¶

  1. Ignore the tail of the distribution of each feature by picking values between 10% quantile to 90% quantile. Let us call these values to set S.
  2. Find the mean and standard deviation of S.
  3. Find the gaussian distribution of S and generate random number equal to the missing values.
  4. Fill random numbers randomly into the place of missing values.

Note that the process define above does not affect the distribution of feature. Moreover, there is no correlation between the features so the above mentioned method would be a better option.¶

Missing values for Class 1:¶

EDA 1. correlation matrix shows that features,'V6','V13','V15','V22','V23','V24','V25','V26','V27','V28','V29' are not correlated with other features.and EDA 2. Box plot and Density curve shows that each feature contains outlier. Moreover, missing values were replaced by 0, so ignore the occurance of 0 than the distribution of features is guassian.

Steps for filling missing values for each feature:¶

Dealing with unco-related features:¶
  1. Ignore the tail of the distribution of each feature by picking values between 10% quantile to 90% quantile. Let call these values to set S.
  2. Find the mean and standard deviation of S.
  3. Find the gaussian distribution of S and generate random number equal to the the missing values.
  4. Fill random numbers randomly into the place of missing values.

Dealing with co-rrelated features:¶

V1 is correlated to 'V2','V3','V5','V7','V9','V10','V18' so we can predict these features by the linear regression on the basis of V1.

Similarly ['V20','V21'], ['V4'],['V8'], ['V16','V17'], ['V19'], ['V11','V12','V14'] can be predicted by ['V22'], ['V1'],['V3'], ['V6'], ['V18'], ['V16'], ['V10'].

Note:¶

  1. V3 is also correlated with other features such as: V5, V7, V9, V10. I could also predict these one by one and use this together with V1 to predict rest. I think this could be a better approach but it will increase the computational complexity. Moreover, Correlation of all of these with V1 is more than abs(0.6). Hence, predicting these by the method I used is also fine. V3 is only one example. There are many others too.

  2. I cannot use the information from V20 to V29 to predict rest of the variables. As they are un-correlated.

fill the missing values¶

In [ ]:
# Dealing with missing values of class 0
feature=['V1','V2','V3','V4','V5','V6','V7','V8','V9','V10','V11','V12','V13','V14','V15'
         ,'V16','V17','V18','V19','V20','V21','V22','V23','V24','V25','V26','V27','V28','V29']
Quantile=df_0.quantile([.1, .9])
import statistics
for f in feature:
    index=df_0.columns.get_loc(f)
    column=[]
    for value in df_0.values[:,index]:
        if value > Quantile[f].values[0] and value < Quantile[f].values[1]:
            column.append(value)
    mean_column= statistics.mean(column)
    stdev_column= statistics.stdev(column)
    m=df_0[f].isnull()
    c=m[m.values==True]

    nan_total=len(c)    
    fill_values = np.random.normal(mean_column,stdev_column,nan_total)
    df_0.loc[m, f] = fill_values

    m=df_1[f].isnull()
    c=m[m.values==True]

    nan_total=len(c)    
    fill_values = np.random.normal(mean_column,stdev_column,nan_total)
    df_1.loc[m, f] = fill_values

        df_predict[f_tst]=df_1[f_tst]
        train=df_predict[df_predict[f_tst].notnull()]
        test=df_predict[df_predict[f_tst].isnull()]
        reg = LinearRegression().fit(train.values[:,0].reshape(-1,1), train.values[:,1].reshape(-1,1))
        fill_values=reg.predict(test.values[:,0].reshape(-1,1))
        m=df_1[f_tst].isnull()
        c=m[m.values==True]

        nan_total=len(c)    
        df_1.loc[m, f_tst] = fill_values.flatten()

PCA to visualize the data in 2D space:¶

In class 1 as well as class 0, the first principal component contains more than 99% of details of data in terms of variance.

  1. It can also be concluded that most of the points of Class 1 lies under the 500 value of 1st principal component.
  2. There is a large amount of overlapping in the Class 1 and Class 0.
  3. In terms of model selection I would prefer to choose polynomial decision boundary rather than linear to correctly identify Class 1, can be seen in the above scatter plot between PCA 1 and PCA 2.
  4. Moreover, selecting a descriptive model, which will predict the probability density funtion of each class would be a better approach.
